g.text: - Names storage locations in memory whose values can change during the execution of a program
- i.e., a variable can be assigned a value, then later updated as the program runs
- A special type of variable that is initialized with a value and cannot be changed once set
- Ensures its value remains fixed, protecting your program from unintended modifications
- Prevents accidental changes that can lead to calculation errors or logical bugs
- a well-named constant (like GRAVITY) makes it clear that the value is not expected to change,
- If the value needs to be changed in multiple places, updating it in one location (if it were not a constant) would
be error prone. Constants avoid this issue by disallowing changes
- Some compilers can optimise code better when it knows that certain values wont change
- We prevent any accidental modifications, ensuing all related calculations use the correct value
- Line 2 would cause a compilation error, ensuring the value remains consistent
